<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-389-386  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 389 386.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  June 26 1989 v23 n26 p83(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Optical computing. (the need for faster computers; includesrelated article on state-of-the-art advances in optical computing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gruenfeld, Lee.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The need for increased speed in computers makes the concept ofoptical computing an attractive future technology sinceelectricity travels through a chip about 500 times slower thanlight in a fiber and 150 times slower than light in an opticalintegrated circuit.andP;  Optical computers use the wave properties oflight rather than the particle properties and use mirrors andprisms to redirect light beams to the proper place.andP;  Beams arethen manipulated by the use of beam splitters, lenses and othersuch devices.andP;  Switching is achieved by optically bistable deviceshaving bistability, nonlinearity and hysteresis.andP;  Regardless ofthe switching technology, optical computers can be made smaller,lighter and simpler, thus less expensive.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Optical ComputersTechnologyFuture of ComputingAnalysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   What is optical computing up against? (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>